## PART I: THE MANIFESTO (Source Text)
**Author:** Bogdan Jacek Góralski
**Location:** Library of the Institute of History, University of Warsaw
**Date:** Warsaw, May 2011 (Original concept: 2009)

### **Energy and Society**

Europe is threatened by a shift towards a colder climate, a conclusion resulting from my comprehensive research conducted independently over the last 10 years. The arrival of cooling will cause an increase in energy demand. No one can explain sudden climate changes, and the greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide is nonsense invented by undereducated or dishonest scientists. Climate changes are perfectly explained by my theory, even those cyclical cooling periods triggered by the full moon.

98% of Earth's CO2 is contained in the oceans and only 2% in the atmosphere. It is oceanic processes stimulated by gravity that are responsible for the increase of CO2 content in the atmosphere and cyclical climate changes. Besides, the rise in global temperature precedes the rise in atmospheric carbon dioxide content, which contradicts the IPCC theory.

CO2 emission permits will cost Poland over 4.5 billion EUR annually. I need 1 percent of this sum to prove, on the grounds of my climate theory, that CO2 emission permits are baseless and unjustified. Let us allocate the saved funds—45 billion EUR over 10 years—to necessary investments in the modern Polish energy industry.

In just 25 years, Poland's accessible hard coal resources will run out, which will limit the supply of electricity and heat by 50%. We will most likely lack the funds for imports. Earth's oil and gas resources will last for 40 years. Global nuclear fuel resources will last for 50 years. The depletion of energy mineral resources will cause an avalanche rise in energy raw material prices. Meanwhile, our energy needs will grow because the population will increase and climate cooling will arrive.

We must bet on renewable energy, which is more expensive now—the power of water, wind, and biogas. In Europe, renewable energy already constitutes over 12.8% of the yield. At present, considering the future, energy production should be located primarily in **biogas and hydroelectric power plants**.

*   The cost of a Megawatt in a biogas CHP plant is currently about 2–3.5 million EUR, with inexhaustible fuel resources provided by developing agriculture.
*   The cost of a nuclear power plant is about 2.5–4.5 million EUR/MW, with fuel resources nearing depletion.

Moreover, biogas plants clean the environment and provide conditions for agricultural development by ensuring a market for raw materials produced by agriculture—fuel for the biogas plant—which stimulates the development of the rest of the economy. Agricultural development doubling the production of energy raw materials (biomass) requires increased employment in the countryside.

Meanwhile, the Polish countryside has died out, and at least **15 million peasant immigrants** are needed to utilize the deserted lands and increase agricultural production. A similar situation prevails throughout the EU, which makes it possible to absorb hundreds of millions of peasant immigrants from the overpopulated states of Asia and Africa. Increasing agricultural production requires increased water supplies. This forces the creation of retention reservoirs, the development of which will be the effect of building small hydroelectric power plants. In small hydroelectric plants, the cost of a megawatt is about 2.5 million EUR. Wind power plants are cheap but not very productive and need frequent regeneration. Local small power plants will reduce transmission costs, which currently amount to 15% of the energy price.

Work should also be done on technologies for obtaining energy from off-balance sheet underground coal deposits without the need to build mines, which requires research. In the meantime, let us modernize high-efficiency coal power plants, whose cost per megawatt of power is currently 1.5 million EUR.

However, all this is not enough, because the currently prevailing social principles praise the unbridled consumption of raw material and energy resources. Nothing limits this consumption, yet it threatens incalculable consequences of a global economic system crash caused by a shortage of energy and raw materials.

**We must work on implementing a global ethical system based on the universal principle of saving all energies.** This will limit the energy needs of our civilization and secure its further existence.

The principle of saving all energies is a derivative of all ethical systems existing on our planet and synthesizes the thoughts of the creators of all religious systems. Do not incite conflicts—save social energy. Keep society efficient in action, and you will find your place in it. Save and make good use of all energies. This principle applies throughout the universe.

Here is what the Buddhist Daisaku Ikeda says about the need for a new ethical system—a new religion:
> *"I am convinced that only a new religion will be able to take on the leadership function in a civilization that combines science and philosophy on a higher plane. However, the religion we need will have to inspire the scientific and philosophical spirit of humanity and will have to meet the needs of the new era. It must be a religion that can transcend the differences between East and West and—binding all humanity into one organism—save the West from its current crisis, and the East from its current difficulties. The discovery of this kind of religion is the most important task facing humanity today."*

Another problem is ensuring the continuity of civilization's development through an appropriate succession of generations supplying our civilization with life energy. Societies of the most civilized countries of the world are aging and dying out. This constitutes a huge economic problem because labor becomes expensive (their products become uncompetitive) and demand dies out. Who will take over the succession after them? Adam Mickiewicz said:
> *"The foundation of Europe is freedom. If European states wish to remove this foundation, not one stone will remain upon another of this edifice, for freedom will move its seat elsewhere."*

Global population growth has occurred in developing countries, and this breeds social problems as we have recently seen in North Africa—riots and revolutions. In developing countries, there is a surplus of young people deprived of chances for a dignified life. The only advice for us is to open borders and allow the free flow of population from poorer countries to those richer and more civilized. Europe can restore its former freedom of settlement and open its borders. For this to bring success rather than chaos and problems, efforts must be increased to develop a universal religious-ethical system that will allow breaking down the civilization and religious barriers dividing different nations.

Thus, we see that the necessity of working on a universal global ethical system results from many premises. This new ethical system will eliminate the sources of religious conflicts and contribute to the easy adaptation of less educated and poor newcomers in the rich world of G-20 countries. The influx of poor population to depopulated rich countries will give these countries a coveted new development impulse—it will give them **new energy**. It will ensure cheap labor and increased demand for economies that currently have unused production capacities. We see, therefore, that salvation for the world of our civilization lies primarily in a new ethical-religious system based on the **principle of saving all energies**—the most important principle of the universe.

The greatest crime against the new ethical system is war. It irretrievably destroys civilization and the balance of societies, which required enormous energy expenditures. If there is to be a revolution, let it be only peaceful, without violence that destroys common heritage. Let us direct war expenditures towards research on community behavior. Let us learn these behaviors and learn to control them—this will bring energy benefits.

In love, too, we are guided by the principle of energy conservation. We choose a partner who will ensure us the best life, which will allow us to save our life energy.

The principle of energy conservation will optimize our lives, including inheritance systems. Once, man was free from inheritance problems—carrying the burden of property. Man was mobile, moving to where living conditions were better. He possessed only personal items, weapons, and clothing; treasure was tribal property. Settled life led to the appearance of inheritance mechanisms. **Climate changes will cause great migrations and with them, real estate will lose its meaning and value.** Knowing this, we can already modify inheritance mechanisms and make society the heir, as in the old days. This will save us trouble and streamline society. Be free and enjoy life, work when it gives you pleasure, save your energy and use it well. Find your place in society and give your life's earnings back to where they came from. This will save and make good use of the energy of your loved ones and develop human civilization. Property inheritance is a relic because it appropriates social energy.

Saving energy means preserving freedom so that no one can force us to break the principles of the new ethics.

From the principle of saving all energies results the necessity of respecting all existence. This causes a requirement for an ethical approach to all aspects of life.

We must base the development of our civilization on the development of **humanitarian agriculture based on solar energy resources**, which will remain inexhaustible for a long time. The masses flowing into Europe will find employment in modern agriculture. This will ensure the harmonious development of our economies because, according to the World Bank, investments in agriculture guarantee five times greater efficiency in eliminating poverty than expenditures on other economic sectors. **Plant food production requires eight times less energy and raw materials than meat production.** The principle of saving energy will therefore contribute to eliminating the greatest problem of our civilization—"I must kill other beings to live." If we become vegetarians, we will live more ethically—we will save Earth's energy resources for future generations. I believe that if we give them a good example, they will recreate our world and we will be born again.

We are Slavs and we must look confidently into the future, for is it not more serene to trust Providence, and since the future is veiled, to trust the bards, so as not to suffer twice: right now and in the future? According to Mickiewicz, two features of Slavs are characteristic: looking back as unity with ancestors and confidently awaiting the future, faith in the highest ideal—the ideal of man in harmony with the environment.

